Warm pools.

A warm pool keeps a buffer of pre-initialized instances standing by, ready to activate quickly on scale-out. Without one, a scale-out trigger has to launch a fresh instance and bootstrap it, which can take several minutes before it's in service; with one, the group takes a ready instance from the pool and it's in service in seconds.

The pooled instances can sit in one of three states. Stopped costs only for storage but is slower to activate, since it does a full boot. Hibernated also costs only for storage but activates fast, because memory is restored from disk. And running costs full compute but activates fastest.

Use warm pools when bootstrap time is the bottleneck for scale-out, with heavy images, large downloads, or long runtime warm-up, and pair them with lifecycle hooks so the warm-up work happens once, before the instance enters the pool, rather than on every scale-out.
